94","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1497":"1497","1320":"1320","1353":"1353","1273":"1273","1295":"1295","England":"Anglie","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Anglie","Burningham, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"Abt 1295–":"omkring 1295–Afdød","1295–Male":"1295–Afdød","–1497":"–1497","1300–Female":"1300–Afdød","1320–1353":"1320–1353","1268–Male":"1268–Afdød","1273–Female":"1273–Afdød","Abt 1295":"omkring 1295","about 1294":"omkring 1294","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1497":"1497","1320":"1320","1353":"1353","1273":"1273","1295":"1295","England":"England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Burningham, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1295–":"circa 1295–Overleden","1295–Male":"1295–Overleden","–1497":"–1497","1300–Female":"1300–Overleden","1320–1353":"1320–1353","1268–Male":"1268–Overleden","1273–Female":"1273–Overleden","Abt 1295":"circa 1295","about 1294":"circa 1294","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1497":"1497","1320":"1320","1353":"1353","1273":"1273","1295":"1295","England":"England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Burningham, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1295–":"about 1295–Deceased","1295–Male":"1295–Deceased","–1497":"–1497","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1320–1353":"1320–1353","1268–Male":"1268–Deceased","1273–Female":"1273–Deceased","Abt 1295":"about 1295","about 1294":"about 1294","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1497":"1497","1320":"1320","1353":"1353","1273":"1273","1295":"1295","England":"England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Burningham, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Spencer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): occupational name for someone who dispensed provisions or money, from Middle English <i>spenser(e)</i>, <i>spencer(e)</i> ‘household steward, butler, almoner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>espenser</i>, Old French <i>despensier</i>). Compare   Spence   and   Spender  . There is some dispute about the origins of the Spencer family, whose most famous member in recent times was the late Princess of Wales, born Lady Diana Spencer (1961–97). Some sources say that they are descended from William the Conqueror's steward, Robert Despencer. What is clear is that by the 15th century they had become prosperous from sheep farming in Northamptonshire. Robert Spencer (died 1627) was said to be the wealthiest man in England. Their titles have included Earls of Sunderland and Earls Spencer; and through the female line the 5th Earl of Sunderland also became Duke of Marlborough in 1733. This connection was the result of the marriage, in 1700, of the 3rd Duke of Sunderland to the daughter of John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough. The youngest son of this union, John Spencer (1708–46), was the father of the 1st Earl Spencer (1734–83)."],"variants":[{"name":"Spence","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a servant employed in the pantry of a great house or monastery, from Middle English <i>spense</i>, <i>spence</i> ‘pantry, larder, storeroom’ (Old French <i>despense</i>, from a Late Latin derivative of <i>dispendere</i>, past participle <i>dispensus</i> ‘to weigh out or dispense’). Compare   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spenser","meanings":["English: variant of   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spender","meanings":["English:","occupational name or status name from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘steward, treasurer’, a shortened form of Middle English, Old French <i>despendour</i>, denoting someone who managed money or supplies. Compare   Spencer  .","alternatively, perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘spender (of money), spendthrift’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Spencer was born about 1295, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Spencer, was 29 and his mother, Unknown De Warstead, was 24. He married Elizabeth Empon. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1295–":"umbes 1295–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","–1497":"–1497","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1320–1353":"1320–1353","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1273–Female":"1273–Surnud","Abt 1295":"umbes 1295","about 1294":"umbes 1294","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1497":"1497","1320":"1320","1353":"1353","1273":"1273","1295":"1295","England":"England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Burningham, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1295–":"noin 1295–Kuollut","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","–1497":"–1497","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1320–1353":"1320–1353","1268–Male":"1268–Kuollut","1273–Female":"1273–Kuollut","Abt 1295":"noin 1295","about 1294":"noin 1294","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1497":"1497","1320":"1320","1353":"1353","1273":"1273","1295":"1295","England":"England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Burningham, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1295–":"environ 1295–Décédé","1295–Male":"1295–Décédé","–1497":"–1497","1300–Female":"1300–Décédée","1